 were bitterly divided among themselves, some being attracted to Pétain as much as to de Gaulle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExileszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aFrenchzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugeeszFrance. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugeeszGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aDunkirk.  aFranco-German armistice.  aFrench servicemen.  aGeneral de Gaulle.  aPétain.  aSecond World War.  aVichy consular officials.  acamps.  aexiles.  arefugees.1 aAtkin, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526120663zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526120663zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526120663/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA